Rating: 1
Here is the real McCoy as it is done in South Texas and Northern Mexico. I make this all the time. It's really easy! Use 4-5 medium Haas avocados. (Black skin is good). They should yield slightly to a little finger pressure. Cut them in half lenghtwise. With a tablespoon, pry out the seed. Scoop out the flesh into a bowl. Mash with a fork or a potato masher until most of the lumps are gone. (NEVER, never make guacamole in a blender or food processer.) Add salt, pepper, and garlic powder to taste. Add chopped onion and chopped tomato to taste. Yes, you can also put in things like chopped cilantro and chopped serrano pepper (never jalapenos). You can also add a bit of lemon juice which, by the way, will keep it from turning black. Another way to keep it green for serving later is to place the seeds halfway in and cover with plastic wrap. With lemon and the seeds, it will keep in the fridge for several hours. A serving tip is to make it sans onion and tomato and then serve it in three strips - tomato, avacado, onion. This is called "a la bandeira" or flag style because the flag of Mexico is red, green, and white.

